</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Ultrasonography (US) is an established modality for intervention. The introduction of microbubble US contrast agents (UCAs) has the potential to further improve US imaging for intervention. According to licensing, UCAs are currently approved for clinical use in restricted situations, but many additional indications have become accepted as having clinical value. The use of UCAs has been shown to be safe, and there is no risk of renal toxic effects, unlike with iodinated or gadolinium contrast medium. Broadly speaking, UCAs can be injected into the bloodstream (intravascular use) or instilled into almost any accessible body cavity (endocavitary use), either in isolation or synchronously. In microvascular applications, contrast-enhanced US (CEUS) enhances delineation of necrotic areas and the vascularized target to improve real-time targeting. The ability of CEUS to allow true assessment of vascularity has also been used in follow-up of devascularizing intervention. In macrovascular applications, real-time angiographic images can be obtained with CEUS without nephrotoxic effects or radiation. In endocavitary applications, CEUS can achieve imaging similar to that of iodinated contrast medium–based fluoroscopy; follow-up to intervention (eg, tubography and nephrostography) can be performed at the bedside, which may be advantageous. The use of UCAs is a natural progression in US-guided intervention. The aim of this article is to describe the indications, contraindications, and techniques of using UCAs as an adjunctive tool for US-guided interventional procedures to facilitate effective treatment, improve complication management, and increase the overall success of interventional procedures.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160123">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160123">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig1.jpeg" height="652" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Intravascular and endocavitary use of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr>s in the kidney. Images of the right kidney with B-mode US (left), <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> with an intravascular <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> (center), and <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> with an endocavitary <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> (right). Intravascular use of a <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> shows the enhancing renal parenchyma (center), whereas endocavitary use of a <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr>, with the <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> instilled into the collecting system via a nephrostomy tube, shows the morphology of the renal collecting system (right).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig2.jpeg" height="747" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Intravascular and endocavitary use of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr>s in an abscess. Images of a hepatic abscess with B-mode US (left), <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> with an intravascular <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> (center), and <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> with an endocavitary <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> (right). Intravascular use of a <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> shows the enhancing hepatic parenchyma surrounding the nonenhancing abscess and the enhancing internal septum (center), whereas endocavitary use of a <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr>, with the <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> instilled through a drainage tube, shows the morphology of the abscess cavity (right).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig3.jpeg" height="771" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> of a hepatic abscess imaged using low-<abbr title="mechanical index">MI</abbr> microbubble-specific mode. Left: Coregistered gray-scale US image shows the abscess as a hypoechoic area with poorly defined margins, thus underestimating the true extent of abscess formation. Right: CEUS-specific image clearly shows a large nonenhancing area (<b>*</b>) for drainage targeting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig4.jpeg" height="849" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Abscess secondary to gallbladder perforation. Left: B-mode US image does not clearly show the abscess and gallbladder perforation. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image shows a multiseptated collection with a defect in the gallbladder wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig5.jpeg" height="874" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-guided drainage of a multilocular hepatic abscess. Left: B-mode US image shows the abscess as a hypoechoic area with poorly defined internal loculi. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image clearly shows nonenhancing loculi (<b>*</b>) for drainage catheter targeting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig6a.jpeg" height="619" width="920" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Intra-abdominal collection with enteric fistula. Endocavitary <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> tubography was performed after insertion of a drainage catheter into the intra-abdominal collection. Split B-mode US (left) and low-<abbr title="mechanical index">MI</abbr> <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific (right) images are shown. <b>(a)</b> Initial tubogram shows adequate drainage catheter location, with <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> filling the collection (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Endocavitary <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> tubogram a few minutes after injection shows transit of microbubbles into the bowel loops (arrows), thus demonstrating an abnormal communication between the intra-abdominal collection and small bowel loops.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig6b.jpeg" height="619" width="954" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Intra-abdominal collection with enteric fistula. Endocavitary <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> tubography was performed after insertion of a drainage catheter into the intra-abdominal collection. Split B-mode US (left) and low-<abbr title="mechanical index">MI</abbr> <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific (right) images are shown. <b>(a)</b> Initial tubogram shows adequate drainage catheter location, with <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> filling the collection (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Endocavitary <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> tubogram a few minutes after injection shows transit of microbubbles into the bowel loops (arrows), thus demonstrating an abnormal communication between the intra-abdominal collection and small bowel loops.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig7.jpeg" height="698" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Subcapsular renal abscess. The boundary (arrows) between the avascular nonenhancing subcapsular collection and the adjacent renal parenchyma is clearly shown on the <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image (right) but not on the B-mode US image (left). This allows needle insertion to be performed confidently and reduces the risk of damaging renal parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig8a.jpeg" height="663" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Pleural effusion. In the thorax, instillation of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> via drainage catheters can be useful to confirm correct tube placement and demonstrate loculation. <b>(a)</b> In an uncomplicated pleural effusion, <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> fills the pleural space freely after administration through the pleural drainage catheter. The lung edge (<b>*</b>) is unenhanced and appears dark. <b>(b)</b> In a loculated effusion, forceful injection does not lead to wider distribution of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> in the pleural cavity. Patient management can be supplemented with thrombolytic instillation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig8b.jpeg" height="663" width="884" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Pleural effusion. In the thorax, instillation of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> via drainage catheters can be useful to confirm correct tube placement and demonstrate loculation. <b>(a)</b> In an uncomplicated pleural effusion, <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> fills the pleural space freely after administration through the pleural drainage catheter. The lung edge (<b>*</b>) is unenhanced and appears dark. <b>(b)</b> In a loculated effusion, forceful injection does not lead to wider distribution of <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> in the pleural cavity. Patient management can be supplemented with thrombolytic instillation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig9.jpeg" height="683" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Biopsy of papillary renal cell carcinoma. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> of the kidney showed a focal lesion. Two previous negative biopsies were performed under CT and B-mode US guidance. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image (right) shows the vascular viable region of the tumor (arrow) more clearly than the B-mode US image (left). <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> enabled this vascular focus to be targeted; histologic analysis of the biopsy specimen confirmed the diagnosis of papillary renal cell carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig10.jpeg" height="662" width="1150" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Large renal cell carcinoma with central necrosis. Left: B-mode US image does not allow differentiation between vascular and avascular portions of the tumor. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image clearly shows the avascular necrotic portion of the tumor (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig11.jpeg" height="537" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-guided biopsy of a transplanted kidney. Left: B-mode US image does not allow differentiation of avascular parenchyma from the remaining renal parenchyma. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image shows nonperfused areas (arrow) due to a sacrificed accessory artery during transplant surgery, thus avoiding misleading histologic diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig12a.jpeg" height="515" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-guided cryoablation of a renal cell tumor. US was performed after initial ablation to study therapeutic efficacy. <b>(a)</b> After initial ablation, <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> image (right) is more sensitive than Doppler US image (left) in demonstrating the presence of vascularity in the treated lesion (arrow), indicating residual viability of the tumor. <b>(b)</b> After a further ablation cycle, <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> image confirms loss of tumor vascularity and successful completion of the treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig12b.jpeg" height="514" width="980" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-guided cryoablation of a renal cell tumor. US was performed after initial ablation to study therapeutic efficacy. <b>(a)</b> After initial ablation, <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> image (right) is more sensitive than Doppler US image (left) in demonstrating the presence of vascularity in the treated lesion (arrow), indicating residual viability of the tumor. <b>(b)</b> After a further ablation cycle, <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> image confirms loss of tumor vascularity and successful completion of the treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig13.jpeg" height="687" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Nephrostomy of a calix. Left: B-mode US image does not clearly show the target calix due to blood clots and pus within the calices. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image shows improved visibility of the target calix by highlighting the nonvascularized renal caliceal system.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig14.jpeg" height="711" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> nephrostography. After successful nephrostomy tube insertion, <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> nephrostography allows diagnostic evaluation. By introducing <abbr title="US contrast agent">UCA</abbr> into the collecting system (<b>*</b>), the ureters (arrows) can be followed almost all the way to the level of the bladder.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig15.jpeg" height="484" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Femoral artery active extravasation. Left: With conventional color Doppler US, assessment of arterial puncture site extravasation can be difficult. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> image better demonstrates slow flow in active puncture site extravasation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig16a.jpeg" height="741" width="1084" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Endoleak in a largely thrombosed internal iliac aneurysm after treatment with multiple embolization coils and a stent-graft. <b>(a)</b> CT image shows a type 2 endoleak arising from the distal internal iliac branches. Note the metallic artifact related to the embolization coils (arrows), which obscures visualization of the aneurysm sac and the endoleak. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> demonstrated the endoleak (arrow) and was used to guide direct thrombin injection with real-time angiographic imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig16b.jpeg" height="741" width="592" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Endoleak in a largely thrombosed internal iliac aneurysm after treatment with multiple embolization coils and a stent-graft. <b>(a)</b> CT image shows a type 2 endoleak arising from the distal internal iliac branches. Note the metallic artifact related to the embolization coils (arrows), which obscures visualization of the aneurysm sac and the endoleak. <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> demonstrated the endoleak (arrow) and was used to guide direct thrombin injection with real-time angiographic imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig17.jpeg" height="428" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. <abbr title="arteriovenous fistula">AVF</abbr> focal stenosis. <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> (right) improves the sensitivity of Doppler US and can be used to distinguish occlusion from tight subocclusive stenosis. This is facilitated by the fact that high-velocity and low-velocity flow phenomena are registered at the same time with <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr> without aliasing and blooming artifacts and without the angle dependence that affects Doppler US (left).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160123/asset/images/large/rg.2017160123.fig18.jpeg" height="623" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Complex renal cyst. Left: B-mode US image shows a focal renal lesion, for which intervention such as biopsy may be indicated. Right: <abbr title="contrast-enhanced US">CEUS</abbr>-specific image conclusively shows lack of vascularity within the lesion, indicating benignity. Intervention with its associated risks was not performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160123&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Barr RG. Off-label use of ultrasound contrast agents for abdominal imaging in the United States. <em>J Ultrasound Med</em> 2013;32(1):7–12.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.7863/jum.2013.32.1.7">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23269705/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Off-label+use+of+ultrasound+contrast+agents+for+abdominal+imaging+in+the+United+States&amp;author=RG+Barr&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=J+Ultrasound+Med&amp;pages=7-12&amp;doi=10.7863%2Fjum.2013.32.1.7&amp;pmid=23269705">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Sidhu PS, Cantisani V, Deganello A, et al. Role of contrast-enhanced ultrasound (CEUS) in paediatric practice: an EFSUMB position statement. <em>Ultraschall Med</em> 2016 Jul 14. [Epub ahead of print]</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Role+of+contrast-enhanced+ultrasound+%28CEUS%29+in+paediatric+practice%3A+an+EFSUMB+position+statement&amp;author=PS+Sidhu&amp;author=V+Cantisani&amp;author=A+Deganello&amp;publication_year=2016+Jul+14&amp;journal=Ultraschall+Med">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Piscaglia F, Nolsøe C, Dietrich CF, et al. The EFSUMB guidelines and recommendations on the clinical practice of contrast enhanced ultrasound (CEUS): update 2011 on non-hepatic applications. <em>Ultraschall Med</em> 2012;33(1):33–59.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1055/s-0031-1281676">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21874631/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+EFSUMB+guidelines+and+recommendations+on+the+clinical+practice+of+contrast+enhanced+ultrasound+%28CEUS%29%3A+update+2011+on+non-hepatic+applications&amp;author=F+Piscaglia&amp;author=C+Nols%C3%B8e&amp;author=CF+Dietrich&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=Ultraschall+Med&amp;pages=33-59&amp;doi=10.1055%2Fs-0031-1281676&amp;pmid=21874631">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lorentzen T, Nolsøe CP, Ewertsen C, et al. EFSUMB g